Introduction ¶

The Netherlands have an extensive rail network with many stations.

The last years more and more businesses and population are concentrating around stations. Also stations are extended with shops, horeca and office facilities to make them more attractive.

Stations are very different:

  • Major hubs in big cities with many perons and many passengers.
  • Local stations in the country side close to a small town in the middle of the fields.

Railnetwok Netherlands in 2018:

Business Problem ¶

The question is what are good candidate stations to invest in facilities, like shops or horeca facilities.
The anwser to this question helps an business invester to make the right investement decisions.
The goal is analyse and cluster the trainstations in the Netherlands based on the characteristic of the stations and thier neighborhood.

Data sources ¶

The required data is: 1) the Dutch train stations and their coordinates 2) the facilities at and around these train stations 3) the population per postal code (=zip code) 4) the coordinates of the Netherlands 5) the postcode for each station.

The data for point 1) is available at the NS API https://www.ns.nl/en/travel-information/ns-api. The NS is the major Dutch train operator. The API provides an Station section with endpoints to:

  • get a list and coordinates of the trainstations
  • get details per station.

Regarding point 2) this information is available via the FourSquare API. Via this API we retrieve the facilities very close to the station. Secondly also we retrieve the facilities in the stations neighorhoud, e.g. like horeca and museums. The stations details endpoint of the NS API will also provide details for each station.

Regarding point 3) the goverment's CBS (Central Bureau Statistcs) provide various data endpoints, including 'Population and households per postal code: https://beta.opendata.cbs.nl/DataPortal/detail/CBS/82245NED. Via this table we retrieve the population per postal code.

Regarding point 4) and 5) the the Nominatim geocoder for OpenStreetMap data from python library geopy is used.

In the Foursquare we explore the venues for the following sub-categories:

  • Arts & Entertainment (4d4b7104d754a06370d81259)
  • College & University (4d4b7105d754a06372d81259)
  • Food (4d4b7105d754a06374d81259)
  • Nightlife Spot (4d4b7105d754a06376d81259)
  • Outdoors & Recreation (4d4b7105d754a06377d81259)
  • Professional & Other Places (4d4b7105d754a06375d81259)
  • Shop & Service (4d4b7105d754a06378d81259)
  • Travel & Transport (4d4b7105d754a06379d81259)

We’ll be querying the number of venues in each category in a 1000m radius around each train station. 1000m is a reasonable walking distance.

Methodology ¶

Based on the business problem, we like to compare the stations.

We like to cluster and categorize the stations on:

  • number of venues around the station
  • number of shops around the station
  • the population close to the station.

This categorization gives insights the population and activities around stations and select stations for a in-depth analysis for investment opportunities.

Determine per station the coordinates latitude and longitude. Secondly retrieve the postal code for each station via geolocator library

In [11]:
def get_postcode_per_location(coordinate):
    coords = coordinate.split(",")
    lon = coords[0]
    lat = coords[1]
    
    location = geolocator.reverse("{}, {}".format(lat,lon))
    locations = location.address.split(",")
    
    return {
        'Lat': lat,
        'Lon': lon,
        'Postcode': locations[len(locations)-2].strip()[0:4],
        'Country': locations[len(locations)-1].strip()
    }

postcodes = []

categories_list=[];
def parse_categories(categories, level=0, max_level=0):
    if level>max_level: return
    out = ''
    out += '-'*level
    for category in categories:
        # print("\nCategory: {}".format(category))
        parse_categories(category['categories'], level+1, max_level)
        categories_list.append((category['name'], category['id']))
    return categories_list

categories_list_df = pd.DataFrame(parse_categories(categories['response']['categories'], 0, 0), columns=["Category", "Id"])
categories_list_df = categories_list_df[~categories_list_df['Category'].isin(['Event', 'Residence'])].reset_index()

Retrieve the venue counts from FourSquare¶

In [32]:
def get_venue_count(lat, lon, radius, categoryId):
    explore_url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&categoryId={}'.format(
                FOURSQUARE_CLIENT_ID, 
                FOURSQUARE_CLIENT_SECRET, 
                FOURSQUARE_VERSION,
                lat,
                lon,
                radius,
                categoryId)

    # make the GET request
    resp = requests.get(explore_url)
    return int(resp.json()['response']['totalResults'])

In [103]:
# Change label numbers to have a logical grouping: from bigger stations to smaller stations
replace_labels = {0:1, 1:0, 2:2, 3:3}
for i in range(len(kmeans_labels)):
    kmeans_labels[i] = replace_labels[kmeans_labels[i]]

# create map
map_clusters = folium.Map(location=[latitude, longitude], zoom_start=7)

# set color scheme for the clusters
x = np.arange(kclusters)
ys = [i + x + (i*x)**2 for i in range(kclusters)]
cluster_colors = ['red', 'blue','green','orange']
radius = [5, 4, 3, 2]

# add markers to the map
markers_colors = []
for lat, lon, poi, cluster in zip(stations_clusters_counts_df['Lat'], 
                                  stations_clusters_counts_df['Lon'], 
                                  stations_clusters_counts_df['Station'], 
                                  stations_clusters_counts_df['Cluster']):
    popupTxt = str(poi) + '<br/>Cluster ' + str(cluster)
    popupHtml = folium.Html(popupTxt, script=True)
    popup = folium.Popup(popupHtml, max_width=150, min_width=50)

    folium.CircleMarker(
        [lat, lon],
        radius = radius[cluster],
        popup = popup,
        color = cluster_colors[cluster],
        fill = True,
        fill_color = cluster_colors[cluster],
        fill_opacity = 0.7).add_to(map_clusters)

The cluster groups the station on size and available vanues in and around the stations:

  • cluster 1 (Red) are the biggest and main stations: large transitions hubs in big cities with a large amount of facilities.
  • cluster 2 (Blue) are the big stations: important stations in bigger cities with a big amount of facilities.
  • cluster 3 (Green) are smaller stations but with some facilities.
  • cluster 4 (Oranje)are small stations in small villages or cities with limited or no facilities.

Discussion ¶

The current approach results into a clear clustering of number of venues around the station.
The smaller stations shows that the majority of venues are of category 'food', 'Professional & Other Places' and 'Shop & Service'. The big stations shows a more spread pattern.

I tried to find any data regarding the numbers of passengers per station. I was expecting that the ration between venues on the station and the number of passengers would provide some indication stations with investment oppertunaties.

As alternative I tried the population around the stations. However to my suprised provides the population (in the stations postal code) no clear additional information. For all categories the population number and spread are very similar.

I noticed that some major stations are filtered out the data. To make the data more complete it must be investigated why the data is filtered out: for example missing coordinates or duplicate station codes.

Conclusion ¶

Foursquare data is provides good insights to cluster the stations on its importance and size based the number of venues around the station.
However additional information are required to get more business insights in the stations:

  • number of (daily) passengers per day per station. Passengers transfering or passengers entring of leaving the train system.
  • rental prices.
